<h1 id="chapter-2--lists">Chapter 2 : Lists</h1>

<ol>
  <li>Find the least element in a given list <em>L</em>.</li>
  <li>Find the greatest element in a given list <em>L</em>.</li>
  <li>Create a list <em>L</em> of integers between <em>i</em> and <em>j</em>.</li>
  <li>Create a list <em>L</em> of prime numbers between <em>i</em> and <em>j</em>.</li>
  <li>Create a list of lists. Eg:
    <div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>L=[[1,2,3],[4,5,6],[7,8,9]]
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>Understand how to plot using pythonâ€™s <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">matplotlib</code>. Simulate the birthday paradox and plot the possibility of failure as we increase the number of students in the class.</li>
  <li>Program a rectangular spiral. You only need to output the list with the desired number of entries:
<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">L=['R','U','L','L','D','D','R','R','R','U','U','U']</code></li>
  <li>Program an outward spiral.</li>
  <li>Create a list comprising of 1000 elements with entries +1 or -1. Find out the segment which adds up to maximum.</li>
</ol>

